I'll create the following file: [38;5;141m/tmp/ralph-worktrees/iter-881/chapter09.04-dermatology-lesion-triage.md[0m[38;5;244m (using tool: write)[0m

[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 9.4: Dermatology Lesion Triage ⭐⭐
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Pilot · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.02–$0.05 per image
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m There are roughly 3.5 billion people on Earth with access to a smartphone camera but not to a dermatologist. In the United States alone, the average wait time for a dermatology appointment is over 30 days. In rural areas, it can stretch to 90 days or more. In many developing countries, there are fewer than one dermatologist per million people.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Meanwhile, skin cancer is the most common cancer worldwide. Melanoma, the deadliest form, has a five-year survival rate above 99% when caught early (stage I) and below 30% when caught late (stage IV). The difference between those outcomes is often a few months of delay. A suspicious mole that gets triaged quickly gets biopsied quickly. One that sits in a referral queue for three months might progress from "watch and wait" to "we need to talk about treatment options."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's the workflow today in most primary care settings: a patient shows their PCP a spot they're worried about. The PCP, who received maybe two weeks of dermatology training in medical school, makes a judgment call. Refer or don't refer. If they refer, the patient joins the queue. If they don't, they hope they were right. Studies suggest PCPs have a diagnostic accuracy of roughly 50-60% for pigmented lesions. That's not great when the stakes are "is this cancer."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Now imagine a different workflow: the patient (or their PCP) takes a standardized photo of the lesion. An AI system analyzes it and returns a triage recommendation within seconds: benign (routine follow-up), suspicious (schedule dermatology within 2 weeks), or urgent (expedite referral). The dermatologist still makes the final diagnosis. But the AI ensures that the urgent cases jump the queue, and the clearly benign cases don't clog it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is triage, not diagnosis. That distinction matters enormously for regulatory strategy, clinical adoption, and system design. You're not replacing the dermatologist. You're helping the system route patients to the dermatologist faster when it matters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: How Computers Classify Skin Lesions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Model Actually Sees
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A skin lesion classification model is, at its core, a pattern recognition system trained on dermoscopic and clinical photographs. It learns to distinguish visual features that correlate with different diagnostic categories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The features that matter for dermatologists (and that models learn to detect) include:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Asymmetry.** Malignant lesions tend to be asymmetric. If you fold the lesion in half along any axis, the two halves don't match. Benign lesions (like common moles) tend to be roughly symmetric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Border irregularity.** Melanomas often have ragged, notched, or blurred borders. Benign lesions tend to have smooth, well-defined edges. The model learns to detect boundary characteristics at multiple scales.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Color variation.** A benign mole is usually one or two shades of brown. Melanomas can contain multiple colors: brown, black, red, white, blue. The presence of multiple colors within a single lesion is a red flag. Models learn color distribution patterns across the lesion area.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dermoscopic structures.** Under dermoscopy (a magnified, polarized-light view of the skin), lesions reveal structures invisible to the naked eye: pigment networks, globules, streaks, blue-white veils, regression structures. Each structure type has diagnostic significance. Models trained on dermoscopic images learn these patterns directly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Diameter and evolution.** Larger lesions and those that change over time are more concerning. A single photograph can capture diameter (with a reference marker), but evolution requires longitudinal comparison, which is a harder problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Classification Taxonomy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most dermatology AI systems classify lesions into categories aligned with clinical decision-making:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Benign.** Common nevi (moles), seborrheic keratoses, dermatofibromas, hemangiomas. No action needed beyond routine monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Suspicious / Atypical.** Dysplastic nevi, lesions with some but not all concerning features. Warrants dermatology evaluation within a reasonable timeframe (weeks, not days).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Malignant / Urgent.** Melanoma, basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma, or lesions with high-confidence malignant features. Needs expedited referral and likely biopsy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For a triage system, you don't need to distinguish between specific benign subtypes or specific malignant subtypes. You need to reliably separate "needs urgent attention" from "can wait" from "probably fine." This is a much more tractable problem than full differential diagnosis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Convolutional Neural Networks for Image Classification
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The workhorse technology here is the convolutional neural network (CNN), specifically architectures designed for image classification. Let me explain what's happening under the hood without getting lost in the math.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A CNN processes an image through a series of layers. Early layers detect simple features: edges, color gradients, texture patterns. Middle layers combine those into more complex features: circular shapes, color transitions, structural patterns. Late layers combine those into high-level concepts: "this looks like a pigment network" or "this border is irregular."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The final layer outputs a probability distribution across your classification categories. For a three-class triage system: P(benign) = 0.85, P(suspicious) = 0.12, P(urgent) = 0.03. You then apply decision thresholds to convert these probabilities into a triage recommendation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectures that work well for this task include:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EfficientNet.** Good accuracy-to-compute ratio. The B0 through B4 variants offer a tradeoff between speed and accuracy. B3 or B4 are common choices for dermatology.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ResNet.** The classic residual network. ResNet-50 or ResNet-101 provide strong baselines. Well-understood, well-supported across frameworks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Vision Transformers (ViT).** Newer architecture that processes images as sequences of patches. Can capture long-range spatial relationships better than CNNs. Requires more training data but achieves state-of-the-art results on large dermatology datasets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Transfer learning is essential here. You start with a model pre-trained on millions of general images (ImageNet), then fine-tune it on your dermatology dataset. This dramatically reduces the amount of labeled dermatology data you need (thousands of images rather than millions).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Skin Tone Problem (This Is Critical)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's where most dermatology AI discussions get uncomfortable, and where you absolutely cannot cut corners.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The vast majority of dermatology training data comes from fair-skinned populations. The ISIC Archive (the largest public dermoscopy dataset), the HAM10000 dataset, and most published dermatology atlases are overwhelmingly composed of images from Fitzpatrick skin types I-III (light skin). Fitzpatrick types IV-VI (darker skin) are dramatically underrepresented.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This creates a real and measurable bias: models trained primarily on light skin perform worse on dark skin. Lesion borders are harder to detect against darker backgrounds. Color features that signal malignancy on light skin may present differently on dark skin. Dermoscopic structures can appear different depending on the surrounding pigmentation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The consequences are not hypothetical. A triage system that works well for light-skinned patients but poorly for dark-skinned patients will either miss urgent cases in darker-skinned populations (dangerous) or over-refer them (wasteful and erosive of trust).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What you must do:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. **Audit your training data** for skin tone distribution. If it's skewed (it probably is), you need to actively acquire or synthesize more diverse data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. **Stratify your evaluation metrics** by Fitzpatrick skin type. Report sensitivity and specificity separately for each skin type group. If performance drops for types IV-VI, you have a problem to fix before deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. **Include skin tone as a metadata field** in your pipeline so you can monitor performance disparities in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. **Be transparent** with clinicians about known limitations. If your model hasn't been validated on darker skin tones, say so explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This isn't just an ethical consideration. It's a clinical safety requirement and, increasingly, a regulatory expectation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Image Quality: The Patient-Submitted Photo Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical dermatology AI research typically uses high-quality dermoscopic images taken by trained professionals with specialized equipment. Real-world triage systems often need to handle patient-submitted smartphone photos. The gap between these two scenarios is enormous.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Patient-submitted photos suffer from:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Inconsistent lighting.** Fluorescent bathroom lights, outdoor sunlight, dim bedroom lamps. Each creates different color casts that can confuse a model trained on standardized lighting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Variable distance and angle.** Too close (blurry), too far (lesion is tiny in the frame), oblique angles (distorted shape).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **No dermoscopy.** Smartphone cameras capture the surface appearance only. The subsurface structures visible under dermoscopy are invisible. This fundamentally limits what the model can detect.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Distracting backgrounds.** Hair, clothing, other skin features, tattoos, jewelry.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compression artifacts.** Messaging apps compress images aggressively. JPEG artifacts can mimic or obscure lesion features.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your system needs either: (a) a quality gate that rejects unusable images with specific feedback ("please retake with better lighting"), or (b) a model robust enough to handle variable quality, or (c) both. Option (c) is the right answer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Regulatory Landscape
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In the United States, a dermatology lesion classification system is a medical device regulated by the FDA. The regulatory pathway depends on what claims you make:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage / prioritization (lower risk).** If you're only reordering a worklist (flagging cases for faster review, not making diagnostic claims), you may qualify for a De Novo or 510(k) pathway. Several products have received clearance for this use case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Diagnostic aid (higher risk).** If you're telling patients or clinicians "this is likely melanoma," that's a diagnostic claim requiring more rigorous clinical validation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical decision support (potentially exempt).** If the system presents information that a clinician must independently evaluate (and the methodology is transparent), it may qualify as a Clinical Decision Support exemption under 21st Century Cures Act criteria. But the boundaries here are actively being litigated.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For this recipe, we're building a triage system: routing patients to appropriate care levels. This is the most defensible regulatory position and the most clinically useful starting point.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Image Capture] → [Quality Check] → [Preprocessing] → [Classification] → [Triage Decision] → [Clinical Routing]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Image Capture.** A standardized photo is taken, either by the patient via a mobile app, by a PCP using a clinic camera, or by a medical assistant using a dermatoscope attachment. Metadata is captured: body location, patient demographics (including skin type), device information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Quality Check.** The image is assessed for minimum quality thresholds: resolution, focus, lighting, framing. Images that fail get specific feedback for retake. This prevents garbage-in-garbage-out.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Preprocessing.** The image is normalized: resized to model input dimensions, color-normalized to reduce lighting variation, cropped to the lesion region (either manually annotated or auto-detected). Hair and artifact removal may be applied.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Classification.** The preprocessed image is fed through the trained model. Output: probability scores across triage categories, plus a confidence score indicating how certain the model is about its prediction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage Decision.** Business logic converts model outputs into clinical recommendations. This includes confidence thresholds (if the model isn't confident enough, escalate to human review), override rules (certain body locations or patient histories always get escalated), and documentation of the reasoning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical Routing.** The triage recommendation is delivered to the appropriate recipient: the referring PCP, the patient, or the dermatology scheduling system. Urgent cases trigger expedited referral workflows. Benign cases get reassurance plus monitoring recommendations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and hosting.** You need to train a custom image classification model on your dermatology dataset (transfer learning from a pre-trained backbone), then host it for real-time inference. SageMaker provides the full lifecycle: training jobs with GPU instances, model registry for versioning, real-time endpoints with auto-scaling. For a triage system handling patient-submitted photos, you need low-latency inference (under 2 seconds for good UX) and the ability to scale with demand. SageMaker endpoints with auto-scaling policies handle this well.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for image storage.** All lesion images are stored in S3 with SSE-KMS encryption. S3 provides the durable, HIPAA-eligible storage layer. Images are organized by patient ID and submission date. Lifecycle policies can move older images to S3 Glacier for cost optimization while maintaining the required retention period.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration and preprocessing.** Lambda handles the event-driven workflow: image arrives in S3, Lambda triggers quality assessment, preprocessing, and inference orchestration. For image preprocessing (resize, normalize, crop), Lambda's compute is sufficient for single images. The 10 GB memory limit accommodates even large clinical photographs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for triage results and metadata.** Each triage assessment produces structured results (scores, recommendations, metadata) that need fast read/write access. DynamoDB provides single-digit millisecond latency for storing and retrieving triage records. The patient-facing app queries DynamoDB for results. Clinician dashboards query it for worklist prioritization.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Rekognition Custom Labels (alternative path).** If you want to avoid managing your own model training infrastructure, Rekognition Custom Labels lets you train an image classifier by uploading labeled images through a console interface. The tradeoff: less control over architecture and hyperparameters, but dramatically simpler operations. For a pilot or MVP, this can get you to clinical validation faster. For production at scale with specific performance requirements, SageMaker gives you more control.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon API Gateway for the mobile/web interface.** The patient-facing app and clinician portal communicate with the backend through API Gateway. It handles authentication, rate limiting, and request routing. Combined with Lambda, it provides a serverless API layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SNS for clinical notifications.** When a lesion is triaged as urgent, SNS delivers notifications to the appropriate clinical team: the referring provider, the dermatology triage nurse, or the scheduling system. Different notification channels (SMS, email, push notification) for different urgency levels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph "Image Capture"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         A[Patient Mobile App] --> B[API Gateway]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         C[Clinic Camera/Dermatoscope] --> B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph "Processing Pipeline"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         B --> D[Lambda: Validate & Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         D --> E[S3: Encrypted Image Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         E --> F[Lambda: Quality Assessment]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         F -->|Pass| G[Lambda: Preprocess & Classify]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         F -->|Fail| H[Return Quality Feedback]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         G --> I[SageMaker Endpoint: Lesion Classifier]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph "Triage & Routing"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         I --> J[Lambda: Apply Triage Logic]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         J --> K[DynamoDB: Store Results]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         K --> L{Urgency Level}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|Urgent| M[SNS: Expedited Referral Alert]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|Suspicious| N[Dermatology Queue - Priority]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|Benign| O[Patient Reassurance + Monitoring]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph "Clinical Interface"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         K --> P[Clinician Dashboard]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         K --> Q[Patient App Results]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Services | SageMaker, S3, Lambda, DynamoDB, API Gateway, SNS, CloudWatch, IAM |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | IAM Permissions | `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `sns:Publish`, `lambda:InvokeFunction` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | BAA | Required. All services handling PHI must be covered under AWS BAA. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Encryption | S3 SSE-KMS for images, DynamoDB encryption at rest, TLS 1.2+ in transit |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | VPC | SageMaker endpoint in VPC with no internet access. Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker Runtime. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | CloudTrail | Enabled for all API calls. Critical for audit trail on triage decisions. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Training Data | Minimum 5,000-10,000 labeled dermoscopy/clinical images across triage categories. Must include diverse skin tones. Consider ISIC Archive as a starting point, supplemented with institution-specific data. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost Estimate | ~$0.02-$0.05 per inference (SageMaker endpoint). ~$200-500/month baseline for a pilot (endpoint + storage + compute). Training: ~$50-200 per training run on ml.p3.2xlarge. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role in This Recipe |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|-------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon SageMaker | Train lesion classification model (transfer learning). Host real-time inference endpoint. Model registry for version management. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon S3 | Store patient-submitted images (encrypted). Store training datasets. Store model artifacts. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Lambda | Orchestrate pipeline: quality check, preprocessing, inference invocation, result storage. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon DynamoDB | Store triage results, patient metadata, assessment history. Fast lookups for clinician dashboard. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon API Gateway | REST API for mobile app and clinician portal. Authentication via Cognito. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon SNS | Urgent case notifications to clinical staff. Configurable by urgency level. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Amazon CloudWatch | Monitor inference latency, error rates, model confidence distributions. Alert on performance degradation. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS KMS | Manage encryption keys for PHI at rest and in transit. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code (Pseudocode Walkthrough)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 1: Receive and Validate the Image Submission
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m When a patient or clinician submits a lesion photo, the system needs to validate the submission before doing anything else. This means checking that the image is actually an image (not a PDF or a text file), that it meets minimum resolution requirements, and that the required metadata is present.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you skip this step, you'll end up running expensive inference on garbage inputs and returning meaningless results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION receive_submission(image_file, metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate the image format (JPEG or PNG only for clinical photos)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF image_file.format NOT IN ["JPEG", "PNG"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN error("Unsupported image format. Please submit JPEG or PNG.")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check minimum resolution (lesion needs enough pixels for meaningful analysis)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF image_file.width < 640 OR image_file.height < 640:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN error("Image resolution too low. Minimum 640x640 pixels.")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate required metadata
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     required_fields = ["patient_id", "body_location", "submission_source"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR EACH field IN required_fields:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF field NOT IN metadata:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             RETURN error("Missing required field: " + field)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Generate unique assessment ID
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     assessment_id = generate_uuid()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store image in S3 with encryption
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     s3_key = "submissions/{patient_id}/{date}/{assessment_id}.jpg"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     UPLOAD image_file TO s3_bucket AT s3_key WITH encryption="aws:kms"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store initial metadata in DynamoDB
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     STORE TO assessments_table:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         assessment_id: assessment_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id: metadata.patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         body_location: metadata.body_location
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         submission_time: current_timestamp()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status: "RECEIVED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         s3_key: s3_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN assessment_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 2: Assess Image Quality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the gate that prevents bad images from reaching the model. A blurry, poorly lit, or improperly framed photo will produce unreliable classification results. Better to reject early and ask for a retake than to return a low-confidence triage recommendation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION assess_image_quality(s3_key, assessment_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Download image from S3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image = DOWNLOAD FROM s3_bucket AT s3_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check focus/sharpness using Laplacian variance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Higher variance = sharper image. Threshold calibrated for smartphone photos.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sharpness_score = compute_laplacian_variance(image)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF sharpness_score < SHARPNESS_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UPDATE assessments_table SET status = "QUALITY_FAILED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality_feedback = "Image is too blurry. Hold camera steady and tap to focus."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "FAIL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check lighting adequacy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Analyze histogram: too dark or too bright means poor lighting
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     brightness = compute_mean_brightness(image)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF brightness < MIN_BRIGHTNESS OR brightness > MAX_BRIGHTNESS:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UPDATE assessments_table SET status = "QUALITY_FAILED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality_feedback = "Lighting is inadequate. Move to a well-lit area without direct glare."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "FAIL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check that a lesion-like region is detectable
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Use a simple segmentation or saliency detection to find the ROI
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     roi_detected = detect_lesion_region(image)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF NOT roi_detected:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UPDATE assessments_table SET status = "QUALITY_FAILED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality_feedback = "Cannot identify lesion in image. Center the lesion in the frame."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "FAIL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check for excessive compression artifacts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     artifact_score = estimate_jpeg_quality(image)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF artifact_score < MIN_QUALITY_SCORE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         UPDATE assessments_table SET status = "QUALITY_FAILED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             quality_feedback = "Image quality too low. Use original photo, not a screenshot or forwarded image."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN "FAIL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     UPDATE assessments_table SET status = "QUALITY_PASSED",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         quality_scores = {sharpness: sharpness_score, brightness: brightness, artifact: artifact_score}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN "PASS"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 3: Preprocess the Image for Model Input
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The classification model expects a specific input format: fixed dimensions, normalized pixel values, and ideally a cropped view centered on the lesion. This step transforms the raw patient photo into something the model can work with.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_for_classification(s3_key):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     image = DOWNLOAD FROM s3_bucket AT s3_key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Detect and crop to lesion region with padding
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The model performs better on cropped lesion images than full-frame photos
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     lesion_bbox = detect_lesion_bounding_box(image)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     padding = 0.2  // 20% padding around the lesion for context
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cropped = crop_with_padding(image, lesion_bbox, padding)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Resize to model input dimensions (typically 224x224 or 299x299)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     resized = resize(cropped, target_size=(299, 299))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Color normalization to reduce lighting variation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Subtract ImageNet mean, divide by ImageNet std (standard for transfer learning)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     normalized = normalize_colors(resized,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Optional: hair removal for dermoscopic images
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (Skip for clinical photos where hair removal can introduce artifacts)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF image_metadata.source == "dermoscope":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         normalized = remove_hair_artifacts(normalized)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN normalized
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 4: Run Classification Inference
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Send the preprocessed image to the trained model and get back probability scores for each triage category. The model outputs raw probabilities; the triage decision logic comes in the next step.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_lesion(preprocessed_image, assessment_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Invoke SageMaker endpoint with the preprocessed image
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The endpoint hosts our fine-tuned EfficientNet-B3 model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = INVOKE sagemaker_endpoint(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         endpoint_name = "dermatology-triage-v2",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         content_type = "application/x-image",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         body = serialize_image(preprocessed_image)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Parse model output: probabilities for each class
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     predictions = parse_response(response)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Expected format:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   "benign": 0.82,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   "suspicious": 0.14,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   "urgent": 0.04,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   "model_version": "v2.3.1",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   "inference_time_ms": 145
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store raw predictions (important for audit trail and model monitoring)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     UPDATE assessments_table SET
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         raw_predictions = predictions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         model_version = predictions.model_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         inference_time_ms = predictions.inference_time_ms
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN predictions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 5: Apply Triage Decision Logic
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is where clinical judgment meets model output. Raw probabilities are converted into actionable triage recommendations using configurable thresholds. The thresholds are intentionally conservative: when in doubt, escalate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION apply_triage_logic(predictions, patient_metadata, assessment_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Confidence check: if the model isn't confident, escalate to human review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     max_probability = MAX(predictions.benign, predictions.suspicious, predictions.urgent)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF max_probability < CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:  // e.g., 0.70
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result = "HUMAN_REVIEW"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason = "Model confidence below threshold. Requires dermatologist review."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         GOTO store_result
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply classification thresholds
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Note: thresholds are asymmetric. We're more aggressive about catching urgent cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF predictions.urgent > URGENT_THRESHOLD:  // e.g., 0.15 (intentionally low)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result = "URGENT"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason = "High probability of malignant features detected."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF predictions.suspicious > SUSPICIOUS_THRESHOLD:  // e.g., 0.30
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result = "SUSPICIOUS"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason = "Atypical features detected. Dermatology evaluation recommended."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF predictions.benign > BENIGN_THRESHOLD:  // e.g., 0.80 (intentionally high)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result = "BENIGN"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason = "No concerning features detected. Routine monitoring recommended."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result = "HUMAN_REVIEW"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reason = "Prediction does not meet any threshold with sufficient confidence."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Override rules based on clinical context
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Certain situations always escalate regardless of model output
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF patient_metadata.history_of_melanoma == TRUE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF triage_result == "BENIGN":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             triage_result = "SUSPICIOUS"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reason = reason + " Escalated due to personal history of melanoma."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF patient_metadata.body_location IN ["scalp", "sole", "nail_bed", "mucous_membrane"]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF triage_result == "BENIGN":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             triage_result = "SUSPICIOUS"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reason = reason + " Escalated due to high-risk anatomical location."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store the triage result
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     store_result:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     UPDATE assessments_table SET
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_result = triage_result,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_reason = reason,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         triage_timestamp = current_timestamp(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status = "TRIAGED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {result: triage_result, reason: reason}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Step 6: Route Based on Triage Result
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The final step delivers the triage recommendation to the right people through the right channels. Urgent cases need immediate attention. Suspicious cases need timely scheduling. Benign cases need patient communication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION route_triage_result(assessment_id, triage_result, patient_metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF triage_result == "URGENT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Notify dermatology triage nurse immediately
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         PUBLISH TO sns_topic "urgent-dermatology-referral":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message = format_urgent_alert(assessment_id, patient_metadata)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             attributes = {urgency: "HIGH", channel: "SMS_AND_EMAIL"}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Create expedited referral in scheduling system
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         CREATE referral:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             priority = "URGENT"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             target_specialty = "Dermatology"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             target_timeframe = "48 hours"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assessment_id = assessment_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Notify referring provider
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         PUBLISH TO sns_topic "provider-notifications":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message = "Urgent dermatology referral created for patient {patient_id}. Lesion triage: URGENT."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF triage_result == "SUSPICIOUS":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Add to dermatology scheduling queue with priority
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         CREATE referral:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             priority = "PRIORITY"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             target_specialty = "Dermatology"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             target_timeframe = "14 days"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assessment_id = assessment_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Notify referring provider
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         PUBLISH TO sns_topic "provider-notifications":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message = "Priority dermatology referral created for patient {patient_id}. Lesion triage: SUSPICIOUS."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF triage_result == "BENIGN":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Send patient reassurance with monitoring guidance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         SEND patient_notification:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             message = "Your skin assessment indicates no immediate concerns. " +
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                       "Continue monitoring for changes in size, shape, or color. " +
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                       "Follow up with your provider if you notice any changes."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             include_monitoring_instructions = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF triage_result == "HUMAN_REVIEW":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Route to dermatology triage nurse for manual review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ADD TO review_queue:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assessment_id = assessment_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             priority = "STANDARD"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reason = "Automated triage inconclusive. Manual review required."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Log the routing action for audit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     UPDATE assessments_table SET
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         routing_action = triage_result,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         routing_timestamp = current_timestamp(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         status = "ROUTED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter09.04-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample Output (JSON)**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "assessment_id": "a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_id": "P-98765",
